Proposed law amends present law to allow the La. State Licensing Bd. for Contractors to
establish an equivalent license to allow a person to engage in plumbing work designated as
a "Certified Plumbing Technician" or similarly-titled license.
Proposed law defines "equivalent license" as a license that to be considered equivalent shall
have all of the following characteristics:
(1) Requires successful passage of a standardized examination demonstrating
competency in plumbing codes, safety, and installation practices.
(2) Requires completion of a minimum number of supervised work hours or experience
sufficient to demonstrate practical competency, as established by rule of the
Louisiana State Licensing Board for Contractors.
(3) Establishes a defined scope of work authorized in accordance with such license.
(4) Requires compliance with all applicable building codes and permitting requirements.
(5) Requires maintenance of insurance policies for workers' compensation and for
general liability in the amount of three hundred thousand dollars for each policy.
(6) May include supervision or project limitations as established by rule.
Present law allows a master plumber to become licensed as such only if he was previously
licensed as a journeyman plumber by the State Plumbing Board.
Proposed law also allows a person to eventually become licensed as a master plumber if he
first held an equivalent license as may be created pursuant to proposed law.
Present law provides that no entity shall engage in the business of plumbing without the
employ of a master plumber.
Proposed law allows such a business to an individual licensed pursuant to proposed law.
Present law provides the fees the State Plumbing Board may fix for the examination,
licensing, and renewal fees for various plumbing licenses.
Proposed law specifies that these fees may be fixed only for licenses and examinations
pursuant to present law.
Present law provides the State Plumbing Board with the power to enjoin any person from
engaging in plumbing work when it appears that the person is violating provisions of present
law.
Proposed law clarifies that this power extends only to those licensed pursuant to present law.
Present law provides for the State Plumbing Board to fine any person performing plumbing
work without a license issued by the Board.
Proposed law provides that the State Plumbing Board may only fine those performing
plumbing work without any license whatsoever.
Present law provides for the licensing of journeymen who have not been previously licensed
who fall under the jurisdiction of the State Plumbing Board.
